<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1908-09-29T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1908-09-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="289" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d289">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 12655/35.</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">British
                                Ambassador</gloss>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1908-09-29"><hi rend="italic">September 29,
                                    1908</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Excellency</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the
                            receipt of your note No. 195, of the 25th instant, with regard to the
                            forthcoming international law conference in London, and to say in reply
                            that the contents of your note will have the department’s
                            consideration.</p>
                        <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Bacon.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>